message: #WeThinkCode second year technical mentors in action at the Johannesburg Campus, giving feedback on first year presentations.

Meet Musa Mashaba, current second year student and future data scientist from Kwa-Thema in Springs, Gauteng.  Musa hopes to work as a data scientist / analyst after obtaining his WeThinkCode_ certification. He is particularly interested in working in sports management, and hopes to one day use Big Data to improve team performance.  "WeThinkCode_ has made a significant difference in my life by giving me the confidence to believe that with all of the knowledge I've gained from the school, I can establish a great career." We are excited to share that our CEO, Nyari Samushonga, will be speaking at this years’ Forbes Woman Africa Leading Women Summit. She will be sitting as part of the panel discussing "The Workplace Is No Longer A Place: Where To From Here?". The overall theme of the summit is ‘Resetting Everything: The New Face of Leadership'.  The summit will be broadcast live on CNBC Africa on Tuesday, 8 March at 15:15 Central African Time. You can register to join the webinar online here: https://leadingwomensummit.co.za/?gclid=CjwKCAiAgvKQBhBbEiwAaPQw3F7uLSfgXqNDqshIWZ1UL_AbDZ1GhY0MLDMRjfa78vMF5w4HMBOFzxoCAEwQAvD_BwE

Last week was quite a busy week for the first year #WeThinkCode students, who had to demo their group projects to their technical mentors on Friday.   Our peer-to-peer, self-directed learning approach requires students to be able to work constructively in teams. Collaborating on projects is a key component of our learning methodology, as we aim to simulate a real workplace.

Our CEO, Nyari Samushonga, shared her insights on how we can democratise how we assign competence in our society, on Ventureburn.  "The reality is that life becomes more difficult for people who failed or did poorly in matric. These young people will make up the majority of those who get lost in the unemployment statistics. It’s no surprise that we, or even the young people themselves, believe they’ve missed the chance for a better life. But, as more institutions create #accessible and #sustainable pathways to meaningful #employment, my hope is that more young people realise that they have options. Options even after failing matric. Options even after passing matric and still not being able to pursue a particular degree because of limited resources, and options even after they’ve made it into their degree and things didn’t work out half way through for whatever reason."

Our graduates come from different walks of life and bring with them, their unique experiences to WeThinkCode_. For Maxine, joining the programme was her golden ticket to starting a new life. Get inspired to move out of your comfort zone as you watch Maxine sharing her story here!

Getting a qualification is not an easy task but hard work is rewarding. Our fast paced learning model can be challenging, but we help you adapt very quickly. Neo can tell you all about it!  "It was challenging at the beginning of my journey at WeThinkCode_, having to adapt to the new world of software engineering. At times I had sleepless nights trying to get stuff working.  But mostly WeThinkCode_ trained me to turn a challenge into an opportunity and helped me understand and discover the correct career path."

Senaki Sekese, originally from rural Lesotho, is one of many dynamic graduates who are showing global companies what African tech talent is made of!  "I am currently working for a newly established company called Workspaceman, situated in the Netherlands. The company offers a solution to co-working spaces like Workshop17 in South Africa, Maliebaan45 in the Netherlands and many more. We build a platform that co-working members can use to book meeting rooms, rent offices, and eventing spaces. I enjoy the problem-solving aspect and the new avenues of investigation that come with each problem. It's even more fulfilling to build something that can be used by tones of people around you, let alone thousands around the globe!"

Today as we remember the brave youth of our past, we also celebrate our talented youth of today; their creativity, energy and ongoing commitment to making our futures better and brighter! Happy #YouthDay to all the inspiring young people out there! Recoding the future.

Lance always wanted to go into programming and WeThinkCode_ gave him the opportunity to make his passion a reality.  "It's an exciting career choice because you get to see something you've created being used by people around the world. You're able to make a positive impact wherever you go by solving problems and using code to better things. I am currently a software engineer working for BBD Software Development. Something that I enjoy most about my work is being able to get experience working on a wide range of different programming languages."

"I am most proud of the fact that I am able to pick up new languages so quickly and contributing positively to the development life cycle."   I believe that WeThinkCode_ graduates are worth hiring. We're able to learn so many coding languages over the course of 2 years. WeThinkCode_ makes sure that we have actual programming experience instead of just teaching us and expecting us to know it."  #wethinkcode #youthmonth #borntocode #wtcgraduates #graduates #graduation #southafrica #students #techafrica #techsa #highereducation #coding #softwaredevelopment #womenthinkcode #womenintechsa  #innovation

The need for technology is growing rapidly across all industries, and the demand for skilled developers is greater than ever. Rafeeq du Toit, one of our students graduating today, speaks on his experience at WeThinkCode_:  “Before WeThinkCode_ I was working in some factory doing menial work and that killed me, it killed my spirit, but this place really saved me. I was struggling a lot with my personal identity and where I fit in society. WeThinkCode_ has really shown me there's more to life than just the place you go.  The most valuable thing I learnt is the ability to teach myself. Before this, I could never learn anything by myself. I always needed a teacher to tell me what to do. I've gained the skill of being proactive and being able to look for answers myself and not rely on someone else.  My future goals in the tech industry are to purely learn as much as I can. I find joy in being able to learn things and being able to solve a new problem every single time.  My advice to the first years is that you should actively try to learn things yourself, go beyond what is expected of you, explore as much as possible, and have the joy of finding out how to solve your assignments in new ways.”   #WTC_Grad2020 #WTC_Alumni

One of our students graduating this Saturday, Naledi Matutuone, speaks on her experience at WeThinkCode_:  “I’m proud to be a WeThinkCode_ graduate because I truly believe there is nothing like WeThinkCode_ in Africa right now. The unique peer-to-peer learning model encourages creativity and knowledge sharing so we become stronger together.    As a new techy in the industry, I want to bring the joy of learning how to code and doing things by yourself to other people. I believe the best gifts and ideas come from people living in strife or difficult situations because they have problems they want to solve.   If I could give advice to the first years I would say: find a friend. I went through my first year struggling on my own. Use your friends, find friends and use them for help - once you know more than your friend, keep sharing that knowledge with others.” #WTC_Grad2020  #WTC_Alumni

You might feel the need to reinvent yourself. Learn a new skill. Or improve one you already have. With #WeThinkCode, you don’t need any prior experience to become a world class expert in tech. Learn more about our program here: https://bit.ly/2zJPKYH

Picture yourself being part of Africa’s top tech talent. Or having access to cutting edge technology and global thought leaders. Visit our website and find out how you can recode your future. https://www.wethinkcode.co.za/

Teamwork makes the dream work. Our peer-to-peer learning model helps you find great mentors in your peers. Keep an eye out for details on our next cohort and how to become part of Africa’s community of top tech talent.

One of the great tools our students learn is how to engage with people in the workplace and speak up for their ideas. This is just one of the ways we are molding Africa’s top tech talent for the future. Partner with us to access the next generation of innovators.

The learning is fast-paced and the reward is worth it. In just 2 years, our students become experts in software development and land incredible jobs at leading SA companies. Learn more about our program here: https://www.wethinkcode.co.za/

Adulting doesn’t have to be boring. When you’re doing what you love, every day feels like an exciting challenge. Take a step towards finding your passion for coding and be part of the next generation of Africa’s top tech talent.

We go beyond teaching our students about programming. Networking is just as important to us. Over the years, our sponsors have been providing professional advice and guidance, and have helped mold some of Africa’s top tech talent. Visit our website to learn more.

No qualifications or work experience? No worries. Our mission is to nurture Africa’s top tech talent. Our tuition free course covers the fundamentals of software development and prepares you for an exciting career. https://www.wethinkcode.co.za/

Staying connected has never been more important, even while we’re apart. Information is coming in rapidly, but there are other ways digital platforms are being used to spread positivity. What have been your ways of connecting with others digitally?
CTRL + ALT + DLT  It’s only a matter of time before the pandemic is over. As we countdown the days, remember to keep a daily log of the things you’re grateful for.

The great thing about technology is having access to the world from the comfort of your own home. Most importantly, it plays a vital role in science and healthcare. As we look to the future, we hope to see new developments that will change the world for the better.

In the tech world, staying safe from a virus requires protective software, being cautious with the sites you visit and enhancing privacy settings. As we apply these rules in the real world, remember that isolation can be a great opportunity to discover new things.

What life will look like when it’s all over? There’s no telling. But right now, people are finding ways to stay stimulated, creative and connected from afar. Tell us how you’ve been using your time to improve yourself and you might inspire someone else.

Lockdown is in full effect and we’ve done our part by shutting down to help reduce the spread of the virus. As we stay indoors and connect virtually, let’s also use this time to discover new ways we can use our digital tools for good.

HOW TO APPLY: We are being flooded with applications and queries this week so here are some answers to your questions.  To apply, please visit https://apply.wethinkcode.co.za/users/sign_up We recommend that you watch this video: https://youtu.be/pycx5vh0P3I  Please follow these instructions, in order to make sure the problem is not on your side. - Sign-up (if you don’t have an email account, create one, we recommend Gmail) - Captcha (Watch this video: https://youtu.be/jwslDn3ImM0) - Check your email (click link to validate your account) - Sign-in (password received is case sensitive - also ensure you do not copy and paste empty spaces on either side of the password) - Phone verification (check your phone, make sure the country code is correct and that your SMS inbox has enough space) - Make sure you read ALL instructions!  If you still have a problem, double check again that you’ve done everything correctly. Most of the time, the issue is on your side. If you cannot find a solution, email us at info@wethinkcode.co.za.

A group from Ember Charter, a Brooklyn-based school, visited our Joburg campus this afternoon. Teams working on gender equality, innovation and technology from the World Bank Group came together to try to better understand how coding bootcamps can effectively recruit and retain women in their programs.  To fill this knowledge gap, they turned to bootcamp providers and digital skills programs across 22 countries, including #WeThinkCode in South Africa, to gather insights and strategies on recruitment, inclusive program design and making connections to the labor market. The objective was to synthesize these findings into a toolkit that bootcamp providers across the world can test and refine while working to increase the share of women who participate in their programs. The findings might also be useful for policymakers working on other types of skills training programs, including technical and vocational training, as well as entrepreneurship accelerators and incubators.  The final result is the Women Wavemakers: Practical Strategies for Attracting and Retaining Women in Coding Bootcamps report, which has just been released on the WBG’s website. A few tips for potential WeThinkCoders_ 1) These games have several levels and are therefore sometimes tiring. Complete as many levels as you can in the time allocated. 2) You can play the first game (10 minutes), and then choose to start the second game (2 hours) at a later stage. Once you have started a game, you have to finish it. 3) Don’t be in a rush to play both games today, applications will be open for a while. Make sure you are fresh and have enough time. 4) When playing the games, make sure you are in a quiet place, and that your computer has a fast and reliable Internet connection. 5) In the absence of instructions, do not panic: this is normal, you can figure it out for yourself. Don't give up or lose hope - you can do this!! 6) Google Chrome is preferred, although the game works on most browsers (download the latest version)

We are excited to announce that we are looking for a passionate and talented individual to join the WeThinkCode_ team from April 2017 as Talent Manager.   This is a critical role at WeThinkCode_ as the success of our programme depends on the quality of the software engineers we source, train and place at our corporate sponsors.   The key responsibilities of the Talent Manager will be to design talent attraction and acquisition strategies, monitor and support student performance & develop multi-disciplined learning strategies to enhance students’ capabilities.  The ideal candidate has experience and expertise in HR, talent management and development, preferably in the software engineering space.  If interested email us at info@wethinkcode.co.za! We are excited to announce our 10 Principles for Success, which inspire us, every day, to be and become the best of who we are.   WeThinkCoders_ use them whether they’re solving coding challenges, discussing ideas for new projects, engaging with their peers or contributing to the community.   Each month, we focus on a new principle. June was Turning Challenges Into Opportunities. We learned techniques on how to develop a growth vs. a fixed mindset, better manage one's time and projects and applying design to programming challenges. We were also honoured to host Jean-Paul Agon, CEO & Chairman of L'Oreal, who addressed the students on how he turned challenges into opportunities since he joined the company in 1978!

The first ever: We Think Code Hackathon took place last week. It was a great success and a huge that you to our students and the BBD guys who came to help out.  The Hackathon took place over three days, non stop programming, where the students had to team up in groups of two to three people per team. They were required to complete two tasks as efficiently as possible with very strict requirements, making use of no external libraries besides stdlib.h which meant they had to create most of their own functions from scratch in C.  Some feedback from the students: - Team CheatCode - "The hackathon is quite challenging but it is a bit fun. We discovered how complex things can be made simple"   - Team Dog Star - "We have learned that there’s always room for improvement" - Team Grizzlies "This has helped us improve on our communication skills and also brush up on our multitasking skills." - Team Black Hole "Time is very important" - Team Code Troopers "We have learned that with better planning we are able to achieve better results" - team Afro Cyntex - "This has been a test of our skills and we are having fun while learning from each other"  The winner of the Hackathon will be announced tomorrow evening at the #WTC_Launch event which will be livestreamed tomorrow at 18:30 on Facebook.

Stories behind our coders  Michael - 19  I finished matric last year (I actually decided to take the test while I was studying for my math prelim). I enjoy coding because I love to find and solve problems. And I always love a good challenge.  WeThinkCode_ is a very different type of challenge. I like how it doesn't matter who you are or where you come from. It doesn't even matter how good your marks were in school. If you have the potential to be a good coder you are being given a chance.   Bootcamp is one big challenge. Time management is probably the greatest, as the Bootcamp is always throwing curveballs at you and trying to see how many different tasks you can juggle at the same time.   Most of the memorable moments I have from the Bootcamp are the times that I spend coding. The atmosphere here is amazing and it is fun to interact with people that are all very similar and yet so diverse. So whether it was teaching the instructors how to dance or do a backflip to doing a flash mob there's always a fun time to be had.  I'd say if you want to be really good at coding you need to keep practicing. I know it sounds cheesy but coding isn't one of those things where you can read a book about it or look at someone else's solution to solve a problem.

Stories behind our coders  Khwezi - 22  I grew up in many different environments. Moving from point A to point B was a trend in my childhood. We only found stability and a home in 2006, in Vosloorus where we currently reside. I was highly shy growing up, I blossomed really late socially in being able to hold conversations with strangers, having emotions, speech reflexes, etc.   This is why, for me, in Bootcamp, the most defining moments were getting to know the people I work with and working as teams. I have always been a terrible team player, but sharing the stories and situations with my fellow Bootcampers really opened my eyes.   Hands down my most memorable moments were learning from one another. Its amazing what one can learn once they take off their earphones, get off their phones and interact with people. I am currently trying to practice this way of life outside of Bootcamp now. Interacting and connecting with the people. Honestly you'd be shocked at how much you can learn just from a simple conversation with the stranger down the street which you formed an opinion on.   All I can say to the prospective coders out there, stop thinking you can do it alone. As capable as you are of doing it alone, it would do you more harm in the long run. You are not alone. Coding is more than intelligence, it's a way of life. A way of community. A culture of collaboration.

Stories behind our coders  Thandeka - 23  I was born and grew up in Soweto. I was raised by a very special woman, my mother, who has always instilled in me the importance of knowledge and working hard for the things you want. Sadly, she is no longer with us, but every lesson she has taught me still remains with me.  I heard about WeThinkCode_ from a friend at work, I had never done any kind of coding but have always been intrigued by the concept. After checking out the website and taking the tests, I just had to give it a try.   The biggest challenge so far has been adjusting to the different approach to learning that they have here at WeThinkCode_. I have been so conditioned for a long time to think and learn in a certain way, whereas here at WeThinkCode_ we are encouraged to be creative, interact and learn from each other.  My goal is to learn as much as I can from as many people as I can.   My favourite quote has always been "YOU TRY, YOU FAIL, YOU TRY, YOU FAIL. THE REAL FAILURE IS WHEN YOU STOP TRYING". So never quit on the things you want, learn from your failures, pick yourself up and TRY AGAIN.

Stories behind our Coders  Jessica - 23  "I grew up in a small township called Tshepisong. I was raised by my mother Busisiwe Mahlambi who has always been my inspiration, my motivator and most of all my hero.  Growing up I enjoyed solving problems. No matter how difficult they seemed, I would solve them. My friends would at times find me playing one game for hours, just to get it right.  The day I set my eyes on the screen to write the first WeThinkCode_ test, I was amazed to see the complexity of the puzzles I had to solve. I had a smile though because I could tell that this was just another problem I needed to solve. And I loved it!  Bootcamp was not easy at first. When I got there I was shy and felt alone because it was my first time being surrounded by so many people and it was a bit difficult for me to socialize. But after a few days, I managed to shake off the shyness and realised how exciting Bootcamp really is. You get to solve many problems as a team and in a short period of time.  The brain is really flexible, don’t be afraid to explore something new in your life. At WeThinkCode_ you are given the chance to let your brain explore and absorb as much information you need to be the best coder you can be."

The path from “not working” to “working” might not be obvious, but with patience you can usually find it."  https://medium.freecodecamp.com/things-i-wish-someone-had-told-me-when-i-was-learning-how-to-code-565fc9dcb329

Stories behind the coders  Gabriel, 24  I have always found it hard to study theory. I am more the hands-on type. I studied a BSc IS at NMMU. I loved programming and excelled at it, but I could not keep up with the electives. In 2014, my 3rd year, I failed to pass and was not allowed back into the course. I then chose the UNISA route. But again I did not fit.   When I heard about WeThinkCode_ it was clear this program was for me: all practical, no theory and a peer to peer learning system.   The Bootcamp was an experience like no other. I set goals to work at least 10 hours each day and to push myself all the time. The vast amount of work covered took me by surprise. Over the course of the 4 weeks, we covered my entire first year and half of my second year of university programming! There was not one day when I felt I could slack off.    My advice to all aspiring coders out there? Never give up! Keep going. There will be days when you will feel that you cannot go anymore and the workload is just too much. Remember that in these times we are the engineers of the future and it is up to us to help shape the future in a positive way. If you don’t give it everything you got, then who will be the next Steve Jobs or Mark Zuckerberg? Strive for greatness, push yourself beyond your limits each day and become the next Mark Zuckerberg.
At Bootcamp, Rule#1, you can't succeed alone! Are you being BRAVE?

Stories behind the Coders  Ian, 21     I come from a family where my parents are divorced and remarried. I started studying zoology at The University of Johannesburg and then decided that it was not for me. Because I have always loved computers and how they work, I started to learn a little bit of coding on my own. I came across WeThinkCode_ and decided to take a chance and go for it!  I worked at my father's restaurant to save some money to be able to get to the Bootcamp everyday.  The most challenging part of the Bootcamp was the time consumption. Waking up every morning to get to campus, but once I'm there, the energy and cooperation of all the coders gave me so much motivation. I learnt so much from the Bootcamp, not just with coding but with socialising with other people who think the same way as you do. I have a lot of goals that I had set during this Bootcamp... I could not achieve all of them yet, but I did achieve one, that is to socialise with everyone and help everyone I possibly could.  To the other potential coders out there, there are so many ways to achieve your dream! WeThinkCode_ is one step closer to achieving it. Just go out and do it!
Working together to solve problems at the Bootcamp. Are you #BornToCode? Sign up today at www.wethinkcode.co.za

Stories behind the coders  Sherwin, 26  I started using computers when I was 9. All I wanted to do at that time was play one game, The Prince of Persia. Growing up I was an introvert, I loved to play on my computer. But not only play, I also learned how to make beats, mix and master. I taught myself graphic design and video editing. When it comes software, I really don’t need a manual. I just love tinkering with it until it does something cool, something I didn’t expect.  My love for technology made me want to study further but due to lack of funds I couldn’t pursue my dream of studying graphic design. I started looking for jobs and one thing they all had in common was the word “advantageous”. They would list a couple skills that would be an advantage for you in getting the job, such as web development, programming in JavaScript, HTML/CSS. I decided that if I can’t afford to study graphic design yet, then I might as well learn programming now. I had to teach myself how to code, and I never once regretted taking that step.  The Bootcamp is really difficult! I have come to realize that it is designed to break you. Not break your mind but more to break your resolve, because everyone wants it. Everyone sacrificed something to be here. But how hard are you willing to work to stay? That’s what defines you here. Nothing worthwhile is ever easy.  If you see a problem, fix it if it’s within your control. If not then don’t complain, because we all know the problem exists. Focus rather on what you CAN solve.

Stories behind the coders  Martha, 25  I am a girl from Dennilton in Limpopo. I decided to study IT because it offers al lot of opportunities and most importantly I wanted to study something that doesn’t limit my capabilities. I enrolled for NDip IT (development software) at Tshwane University of Technology eMalahleni Campus, but unfortunately I couldn't continue with my diploma due to financial issues. A friend of mine told me about the WeThinkCode_ program on Facebook and now here I am. My goal is to one day have my own software company.  IT is regarded as a men’s field of work. To all the women out there, I would like to say that if you really believe IT is for men, then it will remain that way until you change your mindset. Remember you can do anything you put your mind to. Women, let’s be the agents of change and show the world that women can actually code.  My favourite quote is “What the mind of man can conceive and believe, it can do" by Stephen Covey.

Stories behind the coders  Sizwe, 23  “First and foremost, I have always been a gamer at heart. It all began with the console my father bought at the end of nursery school . Those childhood TV Games set me on the road to gaming and a passion towards technology. Somehow, most children grow up with a fondness for gaming because there is always a lesson behind and excitement. My first life-defining moment was when I unexpectedly became Head boy in primary school. This nudged me down a path to achieve what I never thought was possible and push the boundaries of my own limits. I soon followed this path to study accounting at WITS. It was the responsible choice and a choice I thought would make my parents proud. But the responsible option is not always the right option. So I took a two year break to rediscover myself, you could call it a ‘soul searching’ break. This experience was humbling as it taught me several life values, there were moments when I'd feel lost and alone because the answers we need in life often elude us when we need them most. This left me wondering and rethinking many aspects of my life…  As cliche as it may sound, making others happy makes me truly happy. I guess seeing someone smile gives life new meaning. What defines me is that NOTHING DEFINES ME”

Stories behind the coders. Episode 1  Steve, 25  "After school I went straight to varsity to study, however I didn’t like what I was studying. I eventually left to join the working world. Which I greatly enjoyed, I did a lot of job hopping from traffic cameras to being a technician at Apple repairs. Life at the Bootcamp has been full of challenges, but this has given me an opportunity to see that passion and enthusiasm can be contagious. Being part of the first Bootcamp, we are privileged to have an opportunity to assist the staff to decide what works and what doesn’t. There have been many very small defining moments, it is those everyday successes that you have when you are working through your code or you learn something about the system. It is all so exciting. The learning is fast paced and full of "this is how they do it" moments."
